WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.720
People haven't asked me how I know so many people, and so I tell them.

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:15.320
And when they hear what I'm about to describe to you, this is what they say.

00:00:15.320 --> 00:00:19.280
And I used to feel that way too, so if this is you, I want you to know that it doesn't

00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:20.280
have to be that way.

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:24.240
In fact, it can become the best part of your week if you give it a chance.

00:00:24.240 --> 00:00:28.160
I'm Libby Heron, and I'm here to convince you to stop worrying about networking and

00:00:28.160 --> 00:00:30.920
just start making friends.

00:00:30.920 --> 00:00:34.500
Networking is awful, especially if you're an introvert like I am.

00:00:34.500 --> 00:00:39.000
We all know connection is super, super important, but maybe you just feel that connection is

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:40.000
daunting.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:41.000
Just like I did.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:45.439
Most people who know me in our community would tell you that I'm kind of a natural at connecting

00:00:45.439 --> 00:00:46.439
with people.

00:00:46.439 --> 00:00:51.459
I manage data communities, I host a podcast, but if you asked my husband, he would tell

00:00:51.459 --> 00:00:55.680
you I am, in fact, borderline antisocial.

00:00:55.680 --> 00:01:00.840
But in 2021, I got an internship that was pretty much just to meet a ton of people.

00:01:00.840 --> 00:01:01.959
That was my job.

00:01:01.959 --> 00:01:07.599
So after four months of doing that job, I met over 100 new people one-on-one.

00:01:07.599 --> 00:01:12.500
And at that point, asking for a Zoom chat when I bumped into somebody interesting online

00:01:12.500 --> 00:01:14.000
was no longer awkward for me.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:16.120
It was just kind of what I did.

00:01:16.120 --> 00:01:19.040
Even though I was still very, very much an introvert.

00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:24.480
That experience showed me that, at least for me, meeting people just takes practice, right?

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:25.480
So what are we up against?

00:01:26.279 --> 00:01:30.680
First of all, you probably think you're not very good at it, which does not help.

00:01:30.680 --> 00:01:31.680
I believe in you.

00:01:31.680 --> 00:01:32.680
I want you to let that go.

00:01:32.680 --> 00:01:33.680
That's a self-limiting belief.

00:01:33.680 --> 00:01:38.239
So I'm going to look back at my journey and just share what helped me get comfortable

00:01:38.239 --> 00:01:42.599
in the data community, because I'd love everybody to have the loving and supportive data family

00:01:42.599 --> 00:01:43.599
that I have.

00:01:43.599 --> 00:01:48.919
I'm going to share how I found people that I clicked with, how I got them to engage with

00:01:48.919 --> 00:01:54.279
me and other people, and how I connected in an authentic way that felt fun and not like

00:01:54.279 --> 00:01:55.279
complete torture.

00:01:55.279 --> 00:01:57.680
There's no one solution to any of these problems.

00:01:57.680 --> 00:02:02.139
We're all super different people, but I'm going to share what helped me.

00:02:02.139 --> 00:02:05.800
So number one, when I was looking for people to connect with, this is going to sound super

00:02:05.800 --> 00:02:06.800
obvious.

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:09.880
I went where the people were.

00:02:09.880 --> 00:02:12.600
People who are attending community events, whether they're online, like the Posit Data

00:02:12.600 --> 00:02:18.679
Science Hangout, whoop, whoop, or in person, like your local R user group, those people

00:02:18.679 --> 00:02:20.440
are there to meet people.

00:02:20.440 --> 00:02:24.119
You don't have to get over the barrier of receptiveness, right?

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:27.279
Nobody goes to a community event hoping, oh, my gosh, I hope I don't meet any people at

00:02:27.279 --> 00:02:29.240
this community event.

00:02:29.240 --> 00:02:33.740
If I joined a community that didn't feel quite right to me, I just moved on and tried another.

00:02:33.740 --> 00:02:36.160
What do you do when you check out a book at the library and you don't like it?

00:02:36.160 --> 00:02:37.720
Do you give up on reading?

00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:41.320
No, you take the book back and you just get a different one.

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:45.199
If I did connect with people in that community, though, I made sure to connect on LinkedIn,

00:02:45.199 --> 00:02:48.240
get a Zoom chat going, and actually make a friend.

00:02:48.240 --> 00:02:49.240
That's the goal.

00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:50.240
Get to know somebody in person.

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:55.600
Number two, when I look back at how I increased engagement in communities to get people talking,

00:02:55.600 --> 00:03:01.559
I noticed that I was the one frequently engaging myself in either the chat or the live meeting.

00:03:01.559 --> 00:03:03.880
Because communities tend to be sort of pay to play.

00:03:03.880 --> 00:03:08.119
I had to put myself out there, I had to turn on my camera, I had to participate.

00:03:08.119 --> 00:03:11.960
You really have to do that if you want people to be willing to do the same.

00:03:11.960 --> 00:03:13.800
People often say they don't know what to say.

00:03:13.800 --> 00:03:16.520
I don't interact because I don't know what to say.

00:03:16.520 --> 00:03:18.199
Remember that data people like puzzles.

00:03:18.199 --> 00:03:20.919
We like having our brains picked, we like challenges.

00:03:20.919 --> 00:03:21.919
And that's what I did.

00:03:21.919 --> 00:03:26.000
I frequently brought my questions and my challenges to the groups I was in instead of just my

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:29.320
accolades and my presentations and my achievements.

00:03:29.320 --> 00:03:32.759
Because if you wait until you have something impressive to say, you might not ever say

00:03:32.759 --> 00:03:33.759
anything.

00:03:33.759 --> 00:03:36.800
Which leads me very nicely to my third point.

00:03:36.800 --> 00:03:42.039
When I was struggling to make authentic connections, it was because I was too worried about what

00:03:42.039 --> 00:03:43.759
people were going to think of me.

00:03:43.759 --> 00:03:46.720
I needed to practice vulnerability.

00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:51.000
I learned that feigning perfection because you want to be perceived well and being super

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:56.259
professional are just kind of counterintuitive, counterproductive to making friends.

00:03:56.259 --> 00:04:00.800
You might think that perfect professional geniuses are impressive, but what they are

00:04:00.800 --> 00:04:05.080
not is relatable or approachable.

00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:09.440
So I started letting my real life self just kind of ooze out through the cracks of my

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:11.699
professional self, my data professional self.

00:04:11.699 --> 00:04:14.559
Because I'm a whole human being and so are you.

00:04:14.559 --> 00:04:15.559
Shocker.

00:04:15.559 --> 00:04:16.559
Newsflash.

00:04:16.559 --> 00:04:21.079
So getting people more surface area to connect with, sharing more of myself with them, really

00:04:21.079 --> 00:04:24.079
increased my chances of seeing a spark with people.

00:04:24.079 --> 00:04:25.920
Something that we could connect on.

00:04:25.920 --> 00:04:29.880
And this also means that I didn't just stick to talking about data, right?

00:04:29.880 --> 00:04:34.679
In fact, if it helps, this is a list of things that I talk with my data friends about regularly.

00:04:34.679 --> 00:04:37.000
And none of those are data.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:38.000
Data is the air we breathe.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:40.200
That's kind of boring at some point.

00:04:40.200 --> 00:04:41.200
We all do it.

00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:42.200
We don't need to talk about it all the time.

00:04:42.200 --> 00:04:43.200
All right.

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:44.200
This is a huge topic.

00:04:44.839 --> 00:04:46.839
Thanks for coming on this journey of take two with me.

00:04:46.839 --> 00:04:50.920
And this topic is really dear to my heart, so I'd love to chat about it more.

00:04:50.920 --> 00:04:53.799
Feel free to come find me here in person or on Discord.

00:04:53.799 --> 00:04:58.640
And you can find more about me on LinkedIn or my website, DataHumans.Club, where my tiny

00:04:58.640 --> 00:04:59.640
little podcast also lives.

00:04:59.640 --> 00:04:59.640


